Good morning Hornets, and happy last day for the 2019-20 School Year! It is very difficult to believe that we are at this point of the year, but with that being said, I want to take a moment to celebrate everyone for their perseverance throughout the past couple of months and am confident we will all come back to school stronger in the Fall as a result.

Prior to heading off for summer, I hope you have a few minutes to read this week's Harvard Herald. I look forward to reconnecting in August!

Take care,
Tom Cardamone

The safety and health of our students is our number one priority. If you‚Äôre sick, don‚Äôt come in. We will make alternate arrangements. We ask that you wear some form of a mask to cover your nose and mouth.

We will have two separate entrances, one for the girls and one for the boys due to the location of locker rooms. Girls will enter through door #10 (by the greenhouse) and boys will enter through door #19 (South Gym entrance). Park in the faculty lot.

REMINDER: Harvard Community Unit School District 50 is hiring both a Director of Public Relations and Communications and a Communications Specialist.

*The Director of Public Relations and Communications leads the district‚Äôs branding and marketing efforts, coordinates and publicizes achievements, and garners community support for the district‚Äôs mission and goals.

*The Communications Specialist will support our external and internal district communications. The Communications Specialist generates and supports timely, accurate, and relevant communications to all members of the school community. The Communication Specialist is a strong writer with experience in communications, marketing, advertising, education, copywriting, graphic design, web design, photography, video production, or motion graphics.

Apply today through the career page on our website. https://www.cusd50.org/careers/

Help shine a light on our remarkable district!

Harvard Community Unit School District 50 is hiring both a Director of Public Relations & Communications and a Communications Specialist.

*The Director of Public Relations and Communications leads the district‚Äôs branding and marketing efforts, coordinates and publicizes achievements, and garners community support for the district‚Äôs mission and goals.

*The Communications Specialist will support our external and internal district communications. The Communications Specialist generates and supports timely, accurate, and relevant communications to all members of the school community. The Communication Specialist is a strong writer with experience in communications, marketing, advertising, education, copywriting, graphic design, web design, photography, video production, or motion graphics.

Apply today through our career page: https://www.cusd50.org/careers/

post_text:
On Wednesday, WHIW 101.3 FM - Harvard Community Radio‚Äòs Jay Schulz spoke with Superintendent Dr. Corey Tafoya about changes to the end of the school year and summer learning.

They discuss a socially distant parade of scholars for seniors and delayed graduation and prom.

Dr. Tafoya shares the plan to prevent the ‚Äúsummer slide‚Äù of knowledge for students. Harvard students can take three-week summer courses called SOAR (Summer Opportunities for Academic Requirements) to catch up on material they missed due to recent school closures.

Students have the option to participate in one or all three of the sessions. SOAR will be online and free for all students. Students are highly encouraged to attend at least one session to ensure academic success when they return to school in the fall.

#cusd50 #WHIW #HarvardRising

We are seeking a District Vision Itinerant Teacher for Harvard Community Unit School District 50.

JOB SUMMARY:
The Vision Itinerant Teacher serves students who require educational services due to a vision loss. The Vision Itinerant Teacher addresses the educational, communication, functional and social/emotional needs of the student and provides guidance to the student‚Äôs family and school personnel. The Vision Itinerant Teacher travels to multiple buildings to directly serve students and effectively consults with a variety of staff and teams to identify students with visual impairments and to address individual student needs.

QUALIFICATIONS:
Professional Educator License (PEL) or eligible for an appropriate license Endorsement in Blind or Partially Sighted, concentration in visual impairments

Apply today: https://cusd50.tedk12.com/hire/ViewJob.aspx?JobID=83

For those concerned about the use of the video conferencing service Zoom, Harvard Community Unit School District 50 has enabled settings to only allow district cusd50.org accounts to access meetings. The default setting for our meetings only allows the host to share their screen. Furthermore, teachers have the ability to turn off all cameras and audio from anyone in a meeting. Teacher accounts do not allow outside users to phone into a meeting.

Whether in the physical or digital space, the safety and well being of students and staff remain our priority. If you have any technology questions, please email d50technology@cusd50.org.

WHIW 101.3 FM - Harvard Community Radio‚Äòs Jay Schulz speaks with Superintendent Dr. Corey Tafoya about current school closures and the impact of COVID-19 on our community.

Key points from the interview:

--e-Learning is for enrichment and continuity.
--The district has ordered additional internet hotspots for families.
--Meal service will be available at Jefferson Elementary from 9 a.m. to 11 a.m. during Spring Break.
--The district expects school closures to last longer than the current guidelines.
--Teachers and staff are working with students remotely and developing curriculum.
--Facilities staff are deep cleaning all our buildings.

#cusd50 #WHIW #WeDoLearning

Harvard Junior High is accepting students for the REACH program.

Apply at: https://www.cusd50.org/reach/

REACH is Harvard CUSD 50‚Äôs after-school program. It runs in five-week sessions throughout the school year.

-The program runs Monday through Thursday beginning when school dismisses.
-A daily snack is provided after school.
-The program ends promptly at 5:00 p.m.
-Parents/guardians can pick up their student at school or have their student bussed to a neighborhood drop-off location.
-A variety of activities are offered each week, including group activities and projects, extended learning opportunities, homework assistance, and special interest activities.
-Fees are $50 per student per session or $25 for direct-certified students.

Questions?

Courtney Fejedelem
Director of Extended Day Programming & Enrichment
cfejedelem@cusd50.org
815-943-4022 Ext. 2144

This week McHenry County Police Charities, with assistance from Woodstock and Harvard Walmart, made a considerate donation of winter clothing, including snow pants, boots, gloves, and coats to our schools for students in need.

Police also donated time to go sledding with students at Crosby Elementary.

Special thanks to McHenry County Police Charities President John Adams, Officer Ed Kohn, Deputy Sandra Rogers, and Sergeant Aimee Knop for helping make the donation and activities possible.

Thank you to everyone who helps make this community partnership a success.

We are excited to announce Springfield 2020! Sixth, seventh, and eighth-grade students have the opportunity to visit Springfield, Illinois, on April 18 by Deluxe Motor Coach.

The tour includes the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Museum, New Salem Village, Old State Capitol, and Illinois State Military Museum. The cost is $145 and includes all admission fees, lunch, and dinner.

The trip is limited to the first 50 junior high students. For more information, email Deborah Widzisz at dwidzisz1@cusd50.org.
